@startmindmap
title FIG-19-01. Choosing the Right Data Architecture View
!include ../../styles/plantuml-theme.puml
skinparam defaultFontSize 15
skinparam mindmapDiagram {
  BackgroundColor #FFFFFF
  LineColor #333333
}
' Selection rule:
' Start with the current data question.
' Choose the first branch that matches the primary concern.
' Use separate linked views when several concerns matter.
' The chapter table provides fuller audience and companion-view guidance.
* Start with the\ndata question
** Meaning and structure
*** Which business information\nconcepts matter?
**** Conceptual\ninformation view
*** What precise, technology-independent\nstructure is required?
**** Logical ERD
*** How will the data be\nstored in a chosen technology?
**** Physical\ndata model
*** Which shared subjects, classifications\nor controlled values are governed?
**** Master/reference\ndata catalogue
** Movement and traceability
*** Where does data move,\ntransform and rest?
**** Data flow\ndiagram (DFD)
*** Where did a value originate, how was\nit transformed and where is it used?
**** Data lineage\nview
** Governance over time
*** Who is accountable and\nwho performs stewardship?
**** Ownership\nmatrix
*** What happens from creation\nthrough retention and disposal?
**** Data lifecycle\nview
** Before drawing
*** State audience, boundary\nand abstraction level
**** Keep one primary\nquestion per view
*** More than one concern?
**** Use separate linked views\nwith stable names and identifiers
*** Still unclear?
**** Clarify the data boundary\nand architecture decision
' Accessibility notes:
' - Text labels carry the complete meaning; colour is not required.
' - Hierarchy and connecting lines make direction explicit.
' - Short line breaks keep labels readable at book-page width.
' - The figure is a first filter, not a substitute for the chapter table.
@endmindmap
